                  <div class="wf-prose">
                    <p>
                      FAB's salary-transfer programme is the most-asked-about product on this site,
                      and the most-misunderstood. The reason: the marketing pages quote the maximum
                      payout for the highest tier, while most readers will fall in the middle two.
                    </p>
                    <h2>The three salary bands, in AED</h2>
                    <p>
                      The bands haven't moved since 2024, but the qualifying period has — from
                      three months to four — and that change hits the effective payout more than
                      any of the headline numbers.
                    </p>
                    <div class="wf-pullbox">
                      <h4>What you actually receive</h4>
                      <div class="ph-line thick" style="margin-bottom:10px;"></div>
                      <div class="ph-line med" style="margin-bottom:10px;"></div>
                      <div class="ph-line" style="margin-bottom:10px;"></div>
                      <div class="ph-line short"></div>
                    </div>
                    <h2>The qualifying months, and why they matter</h2>
                    <p>
                      Four months of qualifying salary credits, not three. We have screenshots
                      from FAB customer service confirming the change took effect on transfers
                      initiated after 1 January 2026.
                    </p>
                    <blockquote>
                      The bonus pays out 90 days after the fourth qualifying credit — which means
                      a programme started in May pays in October at the earliest.
                    </blockquote>
                    <h2>What we'd do</h2>
                    <p>
                      If you're in the AED 15–25k band and looking at this against ENBD's
